i2c-hid: add quirks for Pixart ASUP1303 (Asus Vivobook M1405YA)

The Pixart 093A:3003 touchpad shipped in Asus Vivobook M1405YA has
firmware that locks up after heavy use (fast scrolling, multi-finger
gestures) and after suspend cycles. The chip stops acknowledging
HID_REQ_RESET, leaving the kernel hanging for 1000ms each rebind
attempt with "device did not ack reset within 1000 ms".

Apply a conservative quirks combo to avoid triggering the firmware
bug:
  - NO_SLEEP_ON_SUSPEND: do not issue HID_REQ_SET_POWER to the chip
    on suspend; the firmware misbehaves on the wake path otherwise.
  - BOGUS_IRQ: tolerate 0xffff input length responses (chip emits
    these when its internal buffer overflows).
  - NO_IRQ_AFTER_RESET: skip the 1000ms IRQ wait after reset; the
    chip never asserts the IRQ line after the reset command.
  - DELAY_WAKEUP_AFTER_RESUME: give the firmware additional time to
    settle before the wake sequence is issued.

Signed-off-by: ms <maulanasodiqin@protonmail.com>
---
 drivers/hid/i2c-hid/i2c-hid-core.c | 5 +++++
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/hid/i2c-hid/i2c-hid-core.c b/drivers/hid/i2c-hid/i2c-hid-core.c
--- a/drivers/hid/i2c-hid/i2c-hid-core.c
+++ b/drivers/hid/i2c-hid/i2c-hid-core.c
@@ -149,6 +149,11 @@ static const struct i2c_hid_quirks {
 		 I2C_HID_QUIRK_BOGUS_IRQ },
 	{ I2C_VENDOR_ID_GOODIX, I2C_DEVICE_ID_GOODIX_0D42,
 		 I2C_HID_QUIRK_DELAY_WAKEUP_AFTER_RESUME },
+	{ 0x093A, 0x3003,
+		 I2C_HID_QUIRK_NO_SLEEP_ON_SUSPEND |
+		 I2C_HID_QUIRK_BOGUS_IRQ |
+		 I2C_HID_QUIRK_NO_IRQ_AFTER_RESET |
+		 I2C_HID_QUIRK_DELAY_WAKEUP_AFTER_RESUME },
 	{ 0, 0 }
 };

